To make requests to undocumented endpoints, you can use `client.get`, `client.post`, and other HTTP verbs.
...
To make requests using undocumented parameters, you may use `// @ts-expect-error` on the undocumented
parameter.
This library doesn't validate at runtime that the request matches the type, so any extra values you
send will be sent as-is.
```
...
To access undocumented response properties, you may access the response object with `// @ts-expect-error` on
the response object, or cast the response object to the requisite type.
Like the request params, we do not
validate or strip extra properties from the response from the API.

# knock-node/README.md at main · knocklabs/knock-node
created: 2021-05-05, last updated: 2025-06-02, [Read more](https://github.com/knocklabs/knock-node/blob/main/README.md)

```
import Knock from '@knocklabs/node';
const client = new Knock({
apiKey: process.env['KNOCK_API_KEY'], // This is the default and can be omitted
});
async function main() {
const response = await client.workflows.trigger('dinosaurs-loose', {
recipients: ['dnedry'],
data: { dinosaur: 'triceratops' },
});
console.log(response.workflow_run_id);
}
main();
...
